                        <h2>Dentist's Office Treatments</h2>
                        <p>
                            A trip to the dentist may be more expensive, but they use methods that can be far more effective and 
                            longer&ndash;lasting than over&ndash;the&ndash;counter solutions. 
                        </p>

                        <h3>In&ndash;Home Treatment</h3>
                        <p>
                            First your dentist makes an impression of your teeth. They then use that to create a tray that you take 
                            home with you in which you place a solution. Part of that solution is a chemical called carbamide peroxide 
                            which is a bleaching agent &ndash; and that&rsquo;s what you sink your teeth into every night as you go to 
                            bed but placing the tray in your mouth. It takes around two weeks to see major differences, and you can 
                            expect them to last for around two years. 
                        </p>

                        <h3>Teeth Bleach</h3>
                        <p>
                            This procedure takes place entirely at your dentist&rsquo;s and utilizes a solution containing hydrogen 
                            peroxide. The peroxide is the active ingredient in teeth bleaching and takes around four visits/treatments 
                            to fully finish (each treatment takes around half an hour).  
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Be aware that the solution is quite powerful and could accidentally burn your gums, so your dentist will 
                            protect them with a special barrier during the visit. There&rsquo;s a second risk too: it can make your 
                            teeth very sensitive. Makers of these solutions try to mitigate those risks by adding potassium nitrate 
                            and fluoride to the mixture.
                        </p>

                    </div>
